Durban - A 37-year-old man was sentenced to a total of 14 years imprisonment following charges of rape, assault with intent to do grievous bodily harm and kidnapping levelled against him by the state in the Pietermaritzburg Regional Court. Mandla Hamilton Hlophe was sentenced to ten years for rape, three years for kidnapping and one year for assault. Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, police spokesperson, said Hlophe had approached a woman at her friend’s house in the Bulwer area and asked her to go with him. “The woman refused to go as he had stabbed her before. He threatened to kill her and forced her to go to his house where he raped her,” Zwane said. A case of rape, assault with intent to do grievous bodily harm and kidnapping was opened at Bulwer police station for further investigation. The docket was transferred to Plessisslaer Family Violence, Child Protection and Sexual Offences Unit for further investigation. “The accused was later arrested and charged accordingly. Bail was successfully opposed and the accused remained in custody until he was sentenced,” Zwane said. Hlophe’s arrested was hailed by Major General Bheki Langa, KZN Acting Police Commissioner. “I commanded the unit for their outstanding investigation that assisted in making sure that the accused remained in prison and kept him away from the community,” he said. Daily News